{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653253"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18565"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18565"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.07,0.18,0.07,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114157"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18565"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96157"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10540"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26203"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114157"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProteins help maintain normal blood pH by acting as buffers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how proteins buffer blood pH?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Histidine residues reversibly bind hydrogen ions","Proteins exchange sodium ions","Proteins permanently bind hydrogen ions","Proteins exchange potassium ions","Proteins neutralise carbonic acid"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe protein buffer system primarily works through \u003Cstrong\u003Ehistidine residues reversibly binding hydrogen ions\u003C/strong\u003E. The imidazole side chain of histidine has a pKa near physiological pH, making it ideal for buffering in the blood pH range of 7.35-7.45.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProteins exchange sodium ions\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eproteins exchange potassium ions\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect as protein buffers work with hydrogen ions, not sodium or potassium ions. \u003Cstrong\u003EProteins permanently bind hydrogen ions\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the binding must be reversible to function as an effective buffer. \u003Cstrong\u003EProteins neutralise carbonic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is not how the protein buffer system works.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProteins, particularly albumin, constitute an important buffer system in blood. Their buffering capacity comes primarily from the histidine amino acid residues, which can reversibly accept or donate hydrogen ions to help maintain physiological pH.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Proteins are important buffers in blood that help maintain normal pH.","Histidine amino acids in proteins can reversibly bind hydrogen ions.","The protein buffer system works in the normal blood pH range of 7.35-7.45."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96157"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18565"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96157"},"attributes":{